t: Ezekiel 17
The Eagles and the Vine
And*p the word of the Lord*s came to me, saying,
“Son of man, pose a riddle, and speak a parable to the house of Israel,
and say, ‘Thus says the Lord God:*s “A*pn great eagle with large wings and long pinions, Full*ld of feathers of various colors, Came*ld to Lebanon And*ld took from the cedar the highest branch.
He*ld cropped off its topmost young twig And*ld carried it to a land of trade; He*ld set it in a city of merchants.
Then*ld he took some of the seed of the land And*ld planted it in a fertile field; He*ld placed it*i by abundant waters And*ild set it like a willow tree.

And*ld it grew and became a spreading vine of low stature; Its*ld branches turned toward him, But*ld its roots were under it. So*ld it became a vine, Brought*ld forth branches, And*ld put forth shoots.

“But*ln there was another great eagle with large wings and many feathers; And*ld behold, this vine bent its roots toward him, And*ld stretched its branches toward him, From*ld the garden terrace where it had been planted, That*ld he might water it.
It*ld was planted in good soil by many waters, To*ld bring forth branches, bear fruit, And*ild become a majestic vine.”’

“Say,*p ‘Thus says the Lord God:*s “Will*pn it thrive? Will*ld he not pull up its roots, Cut*ld off its fruit, And*ld leave it to wither? All*ld of its spring leaves will wither, And*ld no great power or many people Will*ld be needed to pluck it up by its roots.
Behold,*ld it*i is*i planted, Will*ld it thrive? Will*ld it not utterly wither when the east wind touches it? It*ld will wither in the garden terrace where it grew.”’”
Moreover*p the word of the Lord*s came to me, saying,

“Say now to the rebellious house: ‘Do you not know what these things*i mean?’*i Tell them,*i ‘Indeed the king of Babylon went to Jerusalem and took its king and princes, and led them with him to Babylon.
And he took the king’s offspring, made a covenant with him, and put him under oath. He also took away the mighty of the land,
that the kingdom might be brought low and not lift itself up, but*i that by keeping his covenant it might stand.

But he rebelled against him by sending his ambassadors to Egypt, that they might give him horses and many people. Will he prosper? Will he who does such things*i escape? Can he break a covenant and still be delivered?

‘As*ip I live,’ says the Lord God,*s ‘surely in the place where*i the king dwells*i who made him king, whose oath he despised and whose covenant he broke—with him in the midst of Babylon he shall die.
Nor will Pharaoh with his*i mighty army and great company do anything in the war, when they heap up a siege mound and build a wall to cut off many persons.
Since he despised the oath by breaking the covenant, and in fact gave his hand and still did all these things,*i he shall not escape.’”
Therefore*p thus says the Lord God:*s “As*i I live, surely My oath which he despised, and My covenant which he broke, I will recompense on his own head.
I will spread My net over him, and he shall be taken in My snare. I will bring him to Babylon and try him there for the treason which he committed against Me.
All his fugitives with all his troops shall fall by the sword, and those who remain shall be scattered to every wind; and you shall know that I, the Lord,*s have spoken.”
Israel Exalted at Last

Thus*p says the Lord God:*s “I will take also one*i of the highest branches of the high cedar and set it*i out. I will crop off from the topmost of its young twigs a tender one, and will plant it*i on a high and prominent mountain.

On the mountain height of Israel I will plant it; and it will bring forth boughs, and bear fruit, and be a majestic cedar. Under it will dwell birds of every sort; in the shadow of its branches they will dwell.

And all the trees of the field shall know that I, the Lord,*s have brought down the high tree and exalted the low tree, dried up the green tree and made the dry tree flourish; I, the Lord,*s have spoken and have done it.”*i
